1. Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA)
How it happens
API endpoints often use object identifiers to retrieve data. BOLA (similar to IDOR) occurs when a user provides an ID they aren't authorized to see, and the server fails to validate ownership of that resource at the code level.
Impact
Unauthorized access leads to data leakage and account takeovers, resulting in financial loss and brand damage.
Practical Example
❌ Vulnerable: The endpoint accepts any user ID without checking if the requester owns it.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule1_v/user/1

Response: 200 OK
{
  "id": 1,
  "username": "John",
  "name": "Scott",
  "flag": "THM{00123123}"
}
Any authenticated user can swap the 1 for another ID and retrieve someone else's data — including sensitive fields like flags and personal info.
✅ Secured: The endpoint now requires an Authorization Token in the header.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule1_s/user/1
Headers: Authorization-Token: bWljaGFlbM6NjAhZUg+UnQ9ZCctOkhlbGxv

Response: 403 Forbidden
{
  "success": "false",
  "cause": "Invalid Authorization Token"
}
Without a valid token tied to that user, the request is rejected.
Mitigation

Implement strict access controls and validate user ownership on every request.
Use unpredictable, random values (UUIDs) for object identifiers instead of sequential integers.


2. Broken User Authentication (BUA)
How it happens
BUA occurs when authentication logic is flawed (e.g., incorrect SQL queries) or security mechanisms like tokens/headers are missing, allowing attackers to escalate privileges.
Impact
Attackers can compromise sessions, masquerade as authorized users, and perform a full account takeover.
Practical Example
❌ Vulnerable: The login endpoint only validates the email and completely ignores the password field.
POST http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule2/user/login_v
Body: email=admin@mht.com | password=ANYTHING

Response: 200 OK
{
  "success": "true",
  "token": "0g*[v;~$1yx5L15J25sm$nm:cAWZv]"
}
An attacker can log in as any user by knowing only their email — the password doesn't matter.
✅ Secured: The updated endpoint validates both email and password before granting access.
POST http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule2/user/login_s
Body: email=admin@mht.com | password=ANYTHING

Response: 401 Unauthorized
{
  "success": "false",
  "cause": "Incorrect Username & Password"
}
Mitigation

Use high-entropy passwords and enforce MFA.
Never expose credentials in GET or POST request parameters.
Use strong JWTs and secure password hashing — never store plain text passwords.


3. Excessive Data Exposure
How it happens
Developers often return a full object from the database, assuming the front-end will filter the data. An attacker can intercept the full API response to see sensitive hidden fields that were never meant to be public.
Impact
Attackers sniff traffic to find account numbers, phone numbers, device info, and access tokens not intended for public view.
Practical Example
❌ Vulnerable: The endpoint returns the full database record, including sensitive fields like device ID and geolocation.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule3/comment_v/1

Response: 200 OK
{
  "id": 1,
  "postid": "1",
  "deviceid": "Android 12.0",
  "latitude": "45.5426274",
  "longitude": "-122.7944111",
  "commenttext": "This is my First Post",
  "username": "baduser007"
}
The app only displays the comment text on the front-end, but the full API response leaks the user's device and precise location.
✅ Secured: The endpoint returns only the fields the client actually needs.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule3/comment_s/1

Response: 200 OK
{
  "postid": "1",
  "commenttext": "This is my First Post"
}
Mitigation

Never rely on the front-end to filter sensitive data — filter it at the API level.
Avoid generic serialization methods like to_string() or to_json() that dump entire objects.


4. Lack of Resources & Rate Limiting
How it happens
APIs fail to restrict the frequency of requests or the size of payloads. This opens the door to Denial of Service (DoS) attacks or excessive resource consumption across network, storage, and compute.
Impact
Targeting Availability, this causes service downtime, financial loss (especially via paid API services like email or SMS), and serious brand damage.
Practical Example
❌ Vulnerable: The "Forgot Password" endpoint sends an OTP with no restrictions on how many times it can be called.
POST http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule4/sendOTP_v
Body: email=test@gmail.com

Response: 200 OK
{
  "success": "true",
  "msg": "4 Digit OTP sent on Email."
}
An attacker can script this to fire thousands of requests, flooding a victim's inbox and running up the company's email marketing bill.
✅ Secured: The updated endpoint enforces a 2-minute cooldown between OTP requests per email address.
POST http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule4/sendOTP_s
Body: email=test@gmail.com

Response: 200 OK  (first request)
{
  "success": "true",
  "msg": "4 Digit OTP sent on Email."
}

Subsequent requests within 2 minutes → 429 Too Many Requests
Mitigation

Use CAPTCHAs to block automated bot scripts.
Define maximum payload sizes and string lengths on all endpoints.
Return 429 Too Many Requests with a Retry-After header when limits are hit.


5. Broken Function Level Authorization (BFLA)
How it happens
A low-privileged user bypasses access checks to reach administrative functions. This typically happens when there is a vague or missing separation between regular user and admin roles in the API logic.
Impact
Attackers gain administrative rights, allowing them to delete users, change system settings, or access sensitive data such as HR records and internal reports.
Practical Example
❌ Vulnerable: The endpoint trusts a client-supplied header to determine admin status.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule5/users_v
Headers: Authorization: YWxpY2U... | isAdmin: 1

Response: 200 OK
[
  { "id": 1, "username": "admin", "name": "Admin User", "role": "admin" },
  { "id": 2, "username": "alice", "name": "Alice" }
]
Alice is a regular HR employee, but by manually adding isAdmin: 1 to her request headers, she gains full admin access to all user records.
✅ Secured: The endpoint ignores the client-supplied header and validates the user's actual role in the database.
GET http://localhost:80/MHT/apirule5/users_s
Headers: Authorization: YWxpY2U... | isAdmin: 1

Response: 403 Forbidden
{
  "success": "false",
  "cause": "You are not an Admin"
}
Mitigation

Deny all access by default — explicitly grant only what is needed.
Always verify user roles and group membership server-side for every sensitive function, never trust client-supplied values.
